      <h2>How Moisture Content Is Measured</h2>
      <p>
        Wood moisture content is expressed as a percentage of the wood's oven-dry weight. Cut a small, representative sample from the board, weigh it on an accurate scale, and record that as the wet weight. Then dry the sample in an oven at 103°C (217°F) until its weight no longer changes — typically 18 to 24 hours — and record that stable weight as the oven-dry weight. The calculator applies the formula MC = ((wet − dry) ÷ dry) × 100 to produce the moisture content percentage.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because the formula is a ratio, the unit you weigh in does not matter as long as you use the same unit for both numbers. Grams and ounces both work, though a digital scale that reads to 0.1 g or better gives the most reliable results for small samples.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Why Wood Moisture Matters</h2>
      <p>
        Wood is hygroscopic — it absorbs and releases water until it reaches equilibrium with the surrounding air. As moisture content changes below the fiber saturation point (around 28–30%), wood shrinks and swells across the grain. Installing wood at the wrong moisture content leads to gaps in flooring, split panels, failed miter joints, and warped tabletops. Matching wood MC to its end-use environment before building is the single most important step in avoiding these failures.
      </p>

      <h2>Oven-Dry Method (Most Accurate)</h2>
      <p>
        The oven-dry method is the reference standard for measuring wood moisture. Weigh a clean offcut, dry it in a lab or kitchen oven at around 103°C, re-weigh it after 24 hours, and re-weigh again every few hours until two consecutive readings match. That stable reading is the oven-dry weight. The method destroys the sample, so always cut an offcut rather than using the workpiece itself. For field work, a pin or pinless moisture meter gives fast readings accurate to within 1–2 percentage points for most species.
      </p>

      <h2>Target MC for Common Uses</h2>
      <p>Match the wood's moisture content to its end-use environment before building:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Exterior construction and outdoor furniture: 12–18%</li>
        <li>Interior furniture: 6–8%</li>
        <li>Flooring: 6–9%</li>
        <li>Cabinetry: 6–8%</li>
        <li>Musical instruments: 6–7%</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is wood moisture content?</h3>
      <p>
        Wood moisture content is the weight of water in a piece of wood expressed as a percentage of its oven-dry weight. It is calculated as ((wet − dry) ÷ dry) × 100.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I measure dry weight accurately?</h3>
      <p>
        Dry a small sample in an oven at 103°C for about 24 hours until the weight stabilizes. Use a digital scale that reads to at least 0.1 g for reliable results.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the fiber saturation point?</h3>
      <p>
        The fiber saturation point is the MC at which the cell walls are fully saturated but the cell cavities hold no free water — typically 28 to 30 percent for most species.
      </p>

      <h3>What MC should interior woodworking wood have?</h3>
      <p>
        Wood for indoor furniture, cabinets, and flooring should be at 6 to 9 percent moisture content to match typical indoor humidity and avoid post-installation movement.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I use a moisture meter instead?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Pin and pinless moisture meters are accurate enough for most projects. The oven-dry method is the gold standard used to calibrate meters.
      </p>

